  "prompt": "What is the difference between O- and O+?",
  "response": "O- and O+ refer to blood types within the ABO and Rh blood classification systems.\n\n1. **Blood Type O- (O Negative):**\n   - **Universal Donor:** Individuals with O- blood are considered universal donors, meaning their blood can be donated to people of any other blood type (A+, A-, B+, B-, AB+, AB-, O+, O-). This is because O- blood does not have A or B antigens on the surface of red blood cells, and it is also Rh-negative (lacking the Rh antigen).\n   - **Donation Restrictions:** Since O- blood lacks both A/B antigens and the Rh antigen, it can only receive blood from other O- donors.\n\n2. **Blood Type O+ (O Positive):**\n   - **Common Blood Type:** Approximately 37.4% of the population has O+ blood, making it one of the most common blood types.\n   - **Positive Rh Factor:** O+ blood has the Rh antigen, which means people with O+ blood can donate to those who are Rh-positive, but not to Rh-negative individuals. O+ can be received by people with O+, A+, B+, or AB+ blood types.\n   - **Universal Red Cell Donor:** While O+ is not a universal donor for all, it can still be donated to any Rh-positive individual, making it highly versatile.\n\nIn summary, the main differences between O- and O+ are related to the presence of the Rh antigen: O- lacks the Rh antigen and can donate to all blood types but can only receive O- blood in return, whereas O+ has the Rh antigen and can donate to all Rh-positive blood types but can receive O+ and O- blood.",
